Re: ProMED-mail Heartwater - Kenya: (KJ) caprine 20171204.5481414
-----------------------------------------------------------------
[The posting above presented a media-published article by Dr Joseph Mugachia, DVM, which included the following message: "The illness (heartwater) is also called Ondiri disease because the 1st case in Kenya was diagnosed around the Ondiri swamp in Kikuyu."

We are grateful to Dr Keith Sumption for the following corrective response. - Mod.AS].

It must be pointed out that Ondiri disease, and heartwater, are not the same, even if the agents concerned are related.

Ondiri fever, or bovine petechial fever, is an ehrlichiosis with a completely different distribution pattern in Kenya, restricted to cool high altitude locations where cattle and the wild host (antelope, bushbuck) share common grazing. The Ondiri swamp where it was 1st discovered is close to the Vet Labs in Kabete. The vector (in my view probably _Ixodes lewisi_) is only associated with these high altitude forests and as the forests have been cleared over the past 30 years, so the disease has disappeared. The ehrlichia sp is probably very closely related to Anaplasma (_A. phagocytohila_) on grounds of the host leucocyte preference and morphology. Its presence in Kenya probably relates to the presence of _Ixodes_ ticks in high latitude, cool locations, with some climatic similarity to parts of Europe, which may have been a source millenia ago for the colonization.

Heartwater, on the other hand, is transmitted by _Amblyomma_ ticks, usually in altitudes less than 1600 meters [approx. 1 mi] above sea level, down to the semi-arid rangelands. Infection involves endothelial cells, not phagocytes.

While Ondiri fever appears extinct (but probably lives on where bushbuck live in the high forests), I am happy to know vets in Kenya at least recall the name, if not the history and differences to heartwater.

--
Keith Sumption
Executive Secretary
