[During the 70's of the 20th C., several papers addressing bovine petechial fever (Ondirfi disease) were authored by researchers of the Faculty of Veterinary Science, University of Nairobi and the Veterinary Research Laboratory, Kabete, Kenya. (Ref. 1,2).

The following is the abstract of ref 1, addressing the morphology of the causal agent of Ondiri disease.

Abstract
"A study has been made of the agent of bovine petechial fever, which is primarily a parasite of polymorphonuclear leucocytes. Distinct morphological forms were observed by light and electron microscopy. They were identical in field cases of the disease, in early bovine passage material, in experimental sheep and in cattle receiving infective sheep blood to reproduce the condition. Maturation into giant bodies and groups of mixed types appeared to be more common during the early stages of the disease, whereas the morula type with small bodies predominated later. The organisms divided by binary fission and by condensation within a large body to produce a small body.

"Extrusion of small and large bodies, and some apparent phagocytic activity against the parasite, were observed in the infected cells.

"It is suggested that the agent be placed tentatively in the genus _Cytoecetes_ proposed by Tyzzer (1938), within the tribe _Ehrlichieae_, together with the causal agent of tick-borne fever, the "equine ehrlichia" agent and Tyzzer's vole organism".

References
1. Krauss H, Davies FG, Odegaard OA and Cooper JE. The morphology of the causal agent of bovine petechial fever (Ondiri disease), J Comp Pathol. 1972 Jul;82(3):241-6.

2. Snodgrass DR, Pathogenesis of bovine petechial fever: Latent infections, immunity, and tissue distribution of Cytocetes ondiri. J Comp Pathol. 1975 Oct;85(4):523-30.
- Mod.AS

